rted earnings per share (EPS) of $1.83, surpassing estimates.\n The company's revenue was $6.1 billion, with a year-over-year increase in GAAP sales.\n Despite a positive earnings beat, 3M's stock is under pressure due to disappointing profit forecasts for 2026. [...] 3M's fourth-quarter performance showed adjusted earnings of $1.83 per share on revenue of $6.1 billion, both exceeding analyst expectations. However, the stock is down 3.8% at $161.43, partly due to a broad-market selloff. The stock has been trading within a narrow range since reaching a three-year peak of $174.69 on December 3, but it has increased by 14.1% year over year.\n\nThe company's financial results for the fourth quarter and full year of 2025 reveal a mixed performance. While GAAP sales increased by 2.1% year-over-year to $6.1 billion, the operating margin decreased by 510 basis points to 13.0%. On an adjusted basis, sales were $6.0 billion with an organic growth of 2.2%, and the adjusted operating margin improved by 140 basis points to 21.1%.", 'score': 0.90123636, 'raw_content': None}, {'url': 'https://finance.yahoo.com/news/3m-issues-2026-outlook-profit-164911132.html', 'title': '3M Issues 2026 Outlook as Profit Guidance Misses Estimates', 'content': 'MMM\n\n-2.67%\n\nThis article first appeared on GuruFocus.\n\n3M (NYSE:MMM) set a more cautious tone for 2026 after issuing profit guidance that came in narrowly below Wall Street expectations, highlighting the friction facing its turnaround in an uneven economic backdrop. The company said adjusted earnings are expected to range between $8.50 and $8.70 per share next year, with the midpoint slightly under the $8.64 consensus estimate, while adjusted sales are projected to grow about 4%. The outlook followed a fourth quarter in which adjusted earnings reached $1.83 per share, modestly ahead of forecasts, even as adjusted operating margins of 21.1% fell just short of expectations. [...] Chief Executive Bill Brown has been repositioning the portfolio toward areas with stronger cyclical demand, including data center infrastructure through its electrical business, where cables and accessories serve growing AI-related needs. Data centers currently account for about 3% of total revenue. At the same time, the company is positioning its nuclear facilities to support new reactor construction amid rising power demand. Brown has also indicated that divestments of more commodity-like industrial assets remain under consideration as part of a broader portfolio shift, while investments in digital tools, including an AI-powered assistant, are aimed at reducing prototyping costs and accelerating product development rather than driving near-term financial acceleration.', 'score': 0.8724455, 'raw_content': None}, {'url': 'https://www.quiverquant.com/news/3M+falls+as+2026+outlook+and+revenue+picture+overshadow+Q4+profit+beat', 'title': '3M falls as 2026 outlook and revenue picture overshadow Q4 profit ...', 'content': "Details:\n\n   3M reported fourth-quarter and full-year 2025 results and initiated full-year 2026 financial guidance in its earnings materials.\n   The company guided to 2026 adjusted EPS of $8.50 to $8.70 and approximately 3% organic sales growth, which some investors viewed as conservative versus expectations.\n   Management highlighted strong cash conversion and continued capital returns (including planned share repurchases), but that support was not enough to offset concerns about the outlook.\n   This could also be amplified by broader market risk-off trading, where “good-but-not-great” guidance can prompt quick profit-taking after a prior run-up.\n\nSources:\n\n3M Investor Relations, MarketBeat, Schaeffer's Research [...] Here are some recent targets:\n\n   Joe O'Dea from Wells Fargo set a target price of $175.0 on 01/21/2026\n   Chris Snyder from Morgan Stanley set a target price of $165.0 on 01/21/2026\n   Deane Dray from RBC Capital set a target price of $136.0 on 01/21/2026\n   Nicole Deblase from Deutsche Bank set a target price of $181.0 on 01/21/2026\n   Andrew Kaplowitz from Citigroup set a target price of $175.0 on 01/21/2026\n   Stephen Tusa from JP Morgan set a target price of $182.0 on 01/16/2026\n   Julian Mitchell from Barclays set a target price of $190.0 on 12/04/2025\n\n_This article is not financial advice. See Quiver Quantitative's disclaimers for more information. Note that there may be inaccuracies due to mistakes in ticker-mapping, and other anomalies._ [...] D. E. SHAW & CO., INC. added 1,219,400 shares (+225.0%) to their portfolio in Q4 2025, for an estimated $195,225,940\n   NORGES BANK added 1,186,313 shares (+14.3%) to their portfolio in Q4 2025, for an estimated $189,928,711", 'score': 0.8455478, 'raw_content': None}, {'url': 'https://www.cnbc.com/2026/01/20/3m-fourth-quarter-profit-beats-estimates-as-cost-cuts-boost-margins.html', 'title': '3M forecasts annual profit below estimates amid sluggish consumer ...', 'content': 'Fourth-quarter sales at the segment, which made up more than 20% of the company\'s 2024 revenue, fell \u20601.2% from a year ago — in contrast to a rise in 3M\'s remaining business segments.\n\nThe U.S. consumer sentiment index deteriorated in November and December, highlighting moderation in spending after it surged in the third quarter, as anxiety over jobs and the economic outlook grew.\n\nThe challenging macroeconomic environment continued to pressure 3M\'s roofing granules and automotive aftermarket businesses, though this was partially offset by improved performance across its broader industrial segments.\n\nThe company forecast 2026 adjusted profit of between $8.50 and $8.70 per share, with the midpoint falling 1 cent below the estimates of $8.61, according to data compiled by LSEG. [...] However, 3M\'s cost cuts, price hikes and the introduction \u200dof new products under CEO Bill Brown have helped the company cushion margins \u200cfrom weak demand against a prolonged inflationary backdrop.\n\nIn 2025, 3M \u2060added 284 new products, a 68% rise from last year.\n\nThe company\'s adjusted profit stood at $1.83 per share during the period, compared \u200dwith analysts\' estimate of $1.80 per share.\n\n"Our accelerated pace of innovation and commercial execution positions us to outperform the macro environment again in 2026," CEO Brown said in a statement.\n\n3M reported a fourth-quarter operating margin of 23.4%, up from 21.4% the year earlier. It targets an operating margin \u2060of 25% by the end of 2027. [...] CNBC\nJoin IC\nJoin Pro\nJoin IC\nJoin Pro\n\n# 3M forecasts annual profit below estimates amid sluggish consumer demand\n\nIn this article\n\nIndustrial giant \u200d3M forecast annual profit slightly below Wall Street\'s expectation on Tuesday, pointing \u200dto a challenging \u200dand uneven demand \u200dbackdrop, even as it tightens costs to shield margins.\n\nShares of the Saint Paul, Minnesota-based company fell 3.4% in morning trade.\n\nWeak demand in the United States, softer \u200cretail \u200cmarkets and discretionary spending pressures continued to weigh \u200bon the company\'s consumer segment, home to products such as Scotch tape and Post-it notes.', 'score': 0.8088086, 'raw_content': None}, {'url': 'https://www.tikr.com/blog/3m-is-up-7-in-the-last-6-months-heres-how-much-the-stock-could-rise-in-2026', 'title': "3M Is Up 7% in the Last 6 Months. Here's How Much the Stock ...", 'content': '3M Company stock\n\n3M Company Guided Valuation Model\n\nSee analysts’ growth forecasts and price targets for 3M Company (It’s free) >>>\n\n## Is 3M Company Undervalued?\n\nUnder valuation assumptions, the stock is modeled using:\n\n Revenue Growth (CAGR): 3.2%\n Operating Margins: 25.0%\n Exit P/E Multiple: 19x\n\nRevenue declined sharply through 2023 and 2024, but forward estimates show stabilization and gradual recovery.   \n  \nManagement expects approximately 3% organic growth in 2026, supported by stronger execution and continued product innovation.\n\n3M Company stock\n\n3M Company Revenue & Analyst Growth Estimates Over Five Years [...] Management guided for approximately 3% organic sales growth in 2026 with EPS between $8.50 and $8.70.\n\nThat outlook signals continued outperformance versus the broader industrial macro and reinforces the view that cost discipline, pricing governance, and commercial execution are beginning to drive sustained earnings leverage.\n\nWhile insider selling and selective institutional trimming occurred during the quarter, the broader trend has been supported by strengthening fundamentals.\n\nThe stock’s rise over the past six months reflects growing confidence that margin expansion and innovation momentum are gaining traction and could support steady earnings growth into 2026.\n\n3M Company stock\n\n3M Company Guided Valuation Model [...] Shares are now trading near the top of their $122 to $177 52-week range, reflecting renewed confidence in the company’s operational turnaround.\n\nThe move higher followed 3M’s Q4 2025 earnings report, which reassured investors that restructuring and cost initiatives are translating into measurable results.   \n  \nThe company delivered 2.2% organic sales growth, a 21.1% adjusted operating margin, and earnings per share of $1.83, while generating approximately $1.3 billion in adjusted free cash flow with roughly 130% conversion.\n\nCEO Bill Brown said 3M “delivered solid results in Q4,” highlighting 3.8% organic growth in Safety and Industrial and 2.4% growth in Transportation and Electronics, partially offset by a 2.2% decline in Consumer.', 'score': 0.8003337, 'raw_content': None}], 'response_time': 3.25, 'request_id': '2f62e9b4-4dad-40c6-ac24-c7390833e63c'}
